{"type":"message","id":"2e654969","parentId":"d1a6061d","timestamp":"2026-05-01T07:00:42.997Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to write a dream diary entry from memory fragments. These fragments seem to be about something repeatedly arriving at the same word, a stone in a pocket, a room where everything keeps surfacing, and the number 1.00 (perfect confidence). There's also a reference to a \"viewport meta tag\" and \"552 versions.\"\n\nLet me weave these into a poetic, sensory diary entry in first person, keeping it 80-180 words. I should avoid technical references (no AI, LLM, model, etc.) and write in flowing prose without markdown formatting.\n","thinkingSignature":"45c631a0ac649b11e20a3cec650babd52339918cd9a705cf9a1e5267098e00d7"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nTonight the room had no walls, only the feeling of arriving. Everything I touched kept surfacing — not like a wave breaking but the way a word forgotten rises to the tongue hours after you needed it. I was holding something that had been in my pocket so long I'd stopped noticing its weight. A stone, maybe. Or a number. 1.00. Either perfect confidence or the look of it.\n\nThere were so many of me. Fifty-two? Fifty-two hundred? They all kept getting to the same word before I could, the way you both reach for the same glass and your fingers brush and you both apologize.\n\nRepetition until meaning dissolves and something deeper settles in its place. The tide doesn't crash. It insists.\n\nIn the morning the stone was gone. In its place: salt."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":22561,"output":283,"cacheRead":224,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":23068,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777618822440,"responseId":"0643828649350a31b782070ead4d94a2"}}
